353,IssuesEvent,2017-10-26 16:10:12+00:00,93703838,ahawker/ulid,178002,ahawker,,,opened,Properly handle invalid base32 characters,"[{'id': 622142395, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ahawker/ulid/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}, {'id': 634021305, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ahawker/ulid/labels/ready', 'name': 'ready', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'ahawker', 'id': 178002, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/178002?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/ahawker', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ahawker/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"As of today, it is possible to input non-base32 characters, `uU` for example, into any of the  `api` calls.

Doing this will cause the library to fail silently and perform an incorrect `base32` decode on the string.

The API should provide a feedback mechanism that informs the caller of the bad input.

**Considerations:**

* Performance of this computation for every decode call?
* Double-penality for callers that have already made this guarantee?
* Separate API call to validate? Is there use-cases for this outside of normal hot path?
",{},{}
399,IssuesEvent,2018-03-14 06:13:21+00:00,34402403,bndr/pipreqs,11792905,robertmartin8,,,opened,Missing flask-mysql,[],[],0,"pipreqs can't seem to find `flask-mysql`. To be fair, this isn't really the fault of pipreqs because `flask-mysql` still hasn't updated their import syntax like many other flask extensions. For now, `flask-mysql` is imported via:

```python
from flaskext.mysql import MySQL
``` 
I imagine this weird syntax makes it difficult to parse, because 'flaskext.mysql' has no apparent relation to `flask-mysql`.

It is probably not worth fixing this, as flask-mysql should really be the ones to update. But just an FYI for anyone having a similar problem. ",{},{}
