2659,IssuesEvent,2017-08-28 22:31:44+00:00,61831189,joshburnett/scanf,22936302,davidpablocohn,,,opened,"Should scanf('%f, %f', '1.4,  2.34') handle leading whitespace?",[],[],0,"Howdy - very grateful for the scanf.py implementation.

My recollection and perusal of the C docs is that scanf should handle leading whitespace for numeric values. Doesn't look like the current implementation does that. I've made minor mods to the defs, e.g.:

    (""%(\d)[di]"", ""([+-]?\d{%s})"", int),
    (""%\*(\d)[di]"", ""(?:[+-]?\d{%s})"", None),
===>
    (""%(\d)[di]"", ""\s*([+-]?\d{%s})"", int),
    (""%\*(\d)[di]"", ""\s*(?:[+-]?\d{%s})"", None),

Which seems to work (I'll admit that some parts of the code remain mysterious to me). Shall I file a change and a pull request? (I'd also love it if it could handle NaNs and Inf, but I have no idea how to implement that, and can work around it in my enclosing code.

Thanks again,
 -pablo

",{},{}
