9284,IssuesEvent,2016-07-15 20:59:20+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,8323700,BoltzmannBrain,1039191,numenta,closed,AttributeError: 'TPShim' object has no attribute 'saveToFile',"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],7,"I've been working on a UDF for kapacitor (https://docs.influxdata.com/kapacitor/v0.13/examples/socket_udf/) by stealing the some of the guts out of the influx.htm example, but have hit a snag when it comes to saving the state of models.  Since kapacitor handles the running process and triggering snapshots, I've been trying to distill what I need from model_checkpoint_mgr from htmengine.

When I run model.save(path), I am getting`AttributeError: 'TPShim' object has no attribute 'saveToFile'`.  I'm reporting this as a possible bug, but realize I could just be doing it wrong too.  If so, let me know.

The code I'm using to test the basics idea is this, which works all the way until the model.save:

```python
  points = influx_points(""cpu"", ""usage_iowait"")
  model = createModel()
  anomalyLikelihood = anomaly_likelihood.AnomalyLikelihood()
  shifter = InferenceShifter()
  for point in points:
    timeString = point[0]
    if ""."" in timeString:
      timeString = timeString.split(""."").pop(0)
    else:
      timeString = timeString.split(""Z"").pop(0)
    timestamp = datetime.strptime(timeString, DATE_FORMAT)

    value = point[1]
    result = model.run({
      ""timestamp"": timestamp,
      ""value"": value
    })
    result = shifter.shift(result)
    inferences = result.inferences
    anomalyScore = inferences[""anomalyScore""]

    likelihood = anomalyLikelihood.anomalyProbability(
          value, anomalyScore, timestamp)

    print {
      ""timestamp"": timestamp.isoformat(),
      ""inferences"": result.inferences,
      ""anomalyLikelihood"": likelihood
    }
  model.save(""/tmp/test"")
```

Edit:  Stacktrace in case it helps
