9930,IssuesEvent,2017-07-19 00:38:20+00:00,84183882,google/sentencepiece,11470708,taku910,1342004,google,closed,"Split longer word, rather than word by word",[],[],2,"Firstly, greatly appreciate your library, it's very useful and easy to to use. But when using i've a trouble,.In Vietnamese vocabulary, a meaning word sometimes includes more than 1 word. For example, sentence  ""I live in Ha Noi"", i want ""Ha Noi"" will stand together after being split. Is there any way or any parameter to handle this case ? Best wishes !",{},{}
9940,IssuesEvent,2018-08-24 09:39:22+00:00,84183882,google/sentencepiece,11470708,taku910,1342004,google,closed,Segfault when importing alongside tensorflow.contrib or pytorch in python (Linux),[],[],3,"Python segfaults when the following code is run (on Ubuntu 16.04 with gcc 5.4.0):
```
import sentencepiece
import tensorflow.contrib
```
Note the segfault does not happen when they are imported in the reverse order.

Probable cause: the quay.io manylinux1 docker image used by the make_py_wheel.sh script has gcc 4.8 (and consequently so does sentencepiece Linux wheel on PyPI), which can be incompatible with binaries made using gcc > 4.9.2. Hence pulling sentencepiece into the same address space as binaries made using 4.9.2 may cause issues like segmentation faults.

More discussion in the pytorch repo (same issue encountered): https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/8358

The ideal solution seems to be to compile and release sentencepiece made with gcc 4.9. If you can update make_py_wheel.sh and/or upload a new version to PyPI, that would be awesome!",{},{}
