11735,IssuesEvent,2018-01-12 04:43:30+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,Don't re-fingerprint codegen'd sources on each run,"[{'id': 422137276, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/performance', 'name': 'performance', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],1,"(this may have already been reported by @baroquebobcat, but I couldn't find the original)

`SimpleCodegenTask` generates output sources from input sources, but currently fingerprints the output sources for the targets it synthetically creates. Since in many cases the synthetic sources are much larger than the inputs (and also much larger than hand-written sources), this can lead to more time spent fingerprinting than is currently avoided with the daemon.

Particularly with the daemon in play, using a synthetic fingerprint for the synthetic target (generated using the fingerprint of the input sources by assuming that the tools are deterministic... perhaps optionally) would avoid re-fingerprinting them each time.

For noop and very-warm cases internally, it looks like this would be something like 50% of the total runtime with the daemon in use (perhaps less without it, since the fingerprinting of the inputs isn't cached in that case).

----

Specifically, the code that causes re-fingerprinting is that the [_inject_synthetic_target](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/src/python/pants/task/simple_codegen_task.py#L213) method creates a synthetic target with an explicit `sources=[x,y,z]` list: underneath the hood, that will result in hitting [this codepath](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/src/python/pants/build_graph/target.py#L842), and calling `Files.create_fileset_with_spec`. If rather than passing `sources=[...]`, we created an `EagerFilesetWithSpec` (which already has a fingerprint), we'd avoid re-fingerprinting.",{},{}
