13052,IssuesEvent,2015-09-22 19:49:21+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,920492,jiffyclub,6392739,conda,opened,py.test 2.7.3+ required for Python 3.5,[],[],0,"Conda currently ships py.test 2.7.2 as the latest version, but that version doesn't work with Python 3.5. I've confirmed that py.test 2.8 does work, and according to the [py.test release notes](http://pytest.org/latest/changelog.html#compared-to-2-7-2) version 2.7.3 should work as well.",{},{}
13058,IssuesEvent,2016-10-21 08:24:34+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,4580257,mick-d,6392739,conda,opened,Conda report wrong package conflicts,[],[],0,"Context: installing a list of packages with `conda` and one package is in conflict with the environment python version
Issue: no matter where in the list the conflicting package is, `conda` systematically reports the first package in the list to be the culprit, even when it is note

Example when `vtk` is the culprit in a python 3.5 environment:
`conda install xlrd matplotlib` works, but:
`conda install xlrd matplotlib vtk` blames xlrd
```
Fetching package metadata .......
Solving package specifications: ....

The following specifications were found to be in conflict:
  - matplotlib
  - python 3.5*
Use ""conda info <package>"" to see the dependencies for each package.
```
`conda install matplotlib xlrd vtk` blames matplotlib
```
Fetching package metadata .......
Solving package specifications: ....

The following specifications were found to be in conflict:
  - matplotlib
  - python 3.5*
Use ""conda info <package>"" to see the dependencies for each package.
```
When actually it is `vtk` to blame:
`conda install vtk` **does not work**
```
Fetching package metadata .......
Solving package specifications: ....

The following specifications were found to be in conflict:
  - python 3.5*
  - vtk
Use ""conda info <package>"" to see the dependencies for each package.
```",{},{}
13065,IssuesEvent,2016-03-01 15:55:48+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1672353,wulmer,6392739,conda,opened,Regression of issue 896,[],[],0,"Hi,

since commit bc9241606ef324f1b926f077fe3940d020d3f013 there is a regression on the previous issue https://github.com/conda/conda/issues/896 where running conda takes endlessly on Windows when Anaconda is installed in a directory not writable by the normal user.

Can anyone explain why the original fix 495ea74fd95bd57a591d907a64c771260a1bdcb7 was reverted a year later in bc9241606ef324f1b926f077fe3940d020d3f013 ?

This makes Anaconda totally unusable in a Windows installation *For all users*.

Wolfgang",{},{}
