13136,IssuesEvent,2016-05-19 16:05:53+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Disable .netrc authentication,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],0,"Anaconda-Server/support#23

When a user has a `~/.netrc` file present, `requests` will use that file to populate the `Authorization` header (using HTTP Basic auth). When authorization fails, conda falls into an infinite loop retrying.

To fix this problem in `anaconda-client`, I disabled `.netrc` authorization by adding a `NullAuth` to the `requests.Session`.

https://github.com/Anaconda-Server/anaconda-client/pull/298",{},{}
13139,IssuesEvent,2016-10-05 20:23:54+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,208217,GaelVaroquaux,6392739,conda,opened,Question: openness of Anaconda Server or local repository tools,[],[],0,"Hi Conda devs,

This is maybe the wrong place to ask the question, but I couldn't find a better place. In particular, my question seems related to information in the [2-years-old blog post on binstar](https://www.continuum.io/blog/developer/binstar-out-beta-now-available-everyone), but it's been siting for 10 days in moderation in the continuum blog.

So, I am trying to understand how different aspects of the conda ecosystem plug together. I've been reading the binstar blog post, which was outlining the technology and aspects of the business model, I wonder how much it is outdated with the conda-forge evolution.

My specific question is: Am I right in thinking that anaconda-server is not open source, as implied in the earlier blog post? If so, what is the roadmap / vision with regards to the open-source ambitions of conda and the community-building behind conda-forge to fill in this specific niche? Are there any recommendation for people who want to have local repositories or mirrors to use conda on them?

Local repositories are described in the [docs on anaconda-repository](https://docs.continuum.io/anaconda-repository/install#start-and-log-on-to-anaconda-server) but it seems to me that they point to non open components of the ecosystem. Mirroring is [also described using these tools](https://docs.continuum.io/anaconda-repository/mirrors-anaconda-repository).

So, is it that these documentations are outdated and there are open ways to replace the central server that conda talks too, or is the recommended way to use the closed anaconda-server? Sorry if I am asking a stupid question, I am trying to get some big picture, and it is a bit hard for me to follow something that is evolving so fast.",{},{}
