13189,IssuesEvent,2018-03-30 23:43:20+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,2774474,epruesse,6392739,conda,opened,Conda installs outdated packages,[],[],0,"**I'm submitting a...**
  - [x] bug report
  - [ ] feature request

## Current Behavior

Conda installs outdated package dependencies if newer versions require more packages to be installed.

I am considering this a bug as the behavior is both unexpected and undesirable:

- Other package managers will refuse to '''remove''' packages, but in an effort to update my packages will install as many packages as needed. This is what I expect. (I also expect a notice if a package cannot be brought to its most recent version because that would require removing another package, but that's a feature to add another day...)
- The entire point of using a package manager is to keep a collection of software packages current. Otherwise I could just download and unpack an ancient tarball and be done with it. Being able to update parts of the dependency tree, e.g. to benefit from bug fixes and performance improvements, is part of the core reason for the existance of package managers.

### Steps to Reproduce

Using e.g. `bmtagger` from Bioconda as example:

```
# set up channels
conda config --system --add channels defaults
conda config --system --add channels conda-forge
conda config --system --add channels bioconda

conda create -n test_env bmtagger
[...]
The following NEW packages will be INSTALLED:

    blast:           2.2.31-1         bioconda   
    bmfilter:        3.101-1          bioconda   
    bmtagger:        3.101-3          bioconda   
    bmtool:          3.101-1          bioconda   
    boost:           1.63.0-py36_2    conda-forge
    bzip2:           1.0.6-1          conda-forge
    ca-certificates: 2018.1.18-0      conda-forge
    certifi:         2018.1.18-py36_0 conda-forge
    extract_fullseq: 3.101-2          bioconda   
    icu:             56.1-4           conda-forge
    libgcc:          7.2.0-h69d50b8_2            
    libgcc-ng:       7.2.0-hdf63c60_3            
    libstdcxx-ng:    7.2.0-hdf63c60_3            
    ncurses:         5.9-10           conda-forge
    openssl:         1.0.2n-0         conda-forge
    pip:             9.0.1-py36_1     conda-forge
    python:          3.6.5-0          conda-forge
    readline:        7.0-0            conda-forge
    setuptools:      39.0.1-py36_0    conda-forge
    sqlite:          3.20.1-2         conda-forge
    srprism:         2.4.24-2         bioconda   
    tk:              8.6.7-0          conda-forge
    wheel:           0.30.0-py36_2    conda-forge
    xz:              5.2.3-0          conda-forge
    zlib:            1.2.11-0         conda-forge
```

Note that an ancient `blast =2.2.31` is installed rather than the current `blast =2.7.1`.

 `bmtagger` does not explicity require a newer version, so using that ancient `blast =2.2.31` is apparently preferred because it only has one dependency, while `blast =2.7.1` has ten.

## Expected Behavior

I expect to get the most current package versions possible under the requirement specifications made.

An argument could be made towards conserving disk space. However, in the example above, `blast 2.2.31` is a monolithic, statically compiled version that unpacks to >400MB on disk, while `blast 2.7.1` only needs 60MB, or 144MB including all of its dependencies.

So in order to minimize package number, an ancient `blast` version is installed and 250MB additional disk space are consumed. 

## Environment Information
```
 active environment : None
          conda version : 4.5.0
    conda-build version : 3.4.2
         python version : 3.6.4.final.0
           channel URLs : https://conda.anaconda.org/bioconda/linux-64
                          https://conda.anaconda.org/bioconda/noarch
                          https://conda.anaconda.org/conda-forge/linux-64
                          https://conda.anaconda.org/conda-forge/noarch
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/main/linux-64
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/main/noarch
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/free/linux-64
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/free/noarch
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/r/linux-64
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/r/noarch
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/pro/linux-64
                          https://repo.anaconda.com/pkgs/pro/noarch
               platform : linux-64
```

```
channels:
  - bioconda
  - conda-forge
  - defaults
```
