13266,IssuesEvent,2017-12-14 23:57:47+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,846274,nh13,6598771,pysam-developers,opened,BAM bin validation exceptions when changing a read to unmapped,[],[],0,"If I set a read to be unmapped, and change no other value, I get the following error when I run picard's ValidateSamFile: `bin field of BAM record does not equal value computed based on alignment start and end, and length of sequence to which read is aligned`.  This is because the bin field is not getting updated when `is_unmapped` is set to `True` (see [this line](https://github.com/pysam-developers/pysam/blob/1ff9e9a9ddb7197c14d4b30d6565a2090d408580/pysam/libcalignedsegment.pyx#L1483)).

I also looked at a few other places where `hts_reg2bin` was getting called and found some issues:
1. [In `reference_start`'s `__set__` method](https://github.com/pysam-developers/pysam/blob/1ff9e9a9ddb7197c14d4b30d6565a2090d408580/pysam/libcalignedsegment.pyx#L1167), we should be checking the unmapped FLAG bit, not call `pysam_get_n_cigar`.  See [note 18 on page 13 in the SAM spc](https://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/SAMv1.pdf).  Also note that when the unmapped field is set, no other assumptions can be made about CIGAR in particular, i.e. it is perfectly valid to have an unmapped read with a CIGAR.  I think it _should_ work, since we call `bam_endpos` when we have cigar elements, but I thought I would still point it out.  In my code, I did try setting `reference_start = reference_start` to trigger the bin update, but I still got errors.
2. Similarly the `__set__` method in `cigartuples` also delegates to `bam_endpos` when calling `hts_reg2bin`.




",{},{}
13279,IssuesEvent,2016-04-14 20:11:26+00:00,12024604,OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE,1681217,ColinDuquesnoy,6609701,OpenCobolIDE,closed,Navigation tree: Assume missing headers,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE/labels/Enhancement', 'name': 'Enhancement', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE/labels/pyqode', 'name': 'pyqode', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}]",[],10,"### Description

The current implementation does not work within copybooks (or programs that have the ""important"" parser parts within copybooks).

It looks like the navigation tree needs a ``DIVISION`` header, otherwise it only contains ""No Data"".

Here's my suggestion:

* If ""No Data"" would be produced check if a section is found instead. If it is ``WORKING-STORAGE``, ``LOCAL-STORAGE``, ``LINKAGE``, ``REPORT`` or ``SCREEN`` assume ``DATA DIVISION``, otherwise assume ``PROCEDURE DIVISION``.
* If no section is found check if you see a possible level number (first word is a numeric word without a dot following), if yes: assume ``DATA DIVISION`` and ``WORKING-STORAGE SECTION``.

This would fix the Navigation tree in most use-cases (the current ""copybook problem"" occurs likely with much production code).

",{},{}
13280,IssuesEvent,2015-06-27 13:46:12+00:00,12024604,OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE,1681217,ColinDuquesnoy,6609701,OpenCobolIDE,closed,[Enhancement] Let the advanced user choose the full path to the compiler,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE/labels/Enhancement', 'name': 'Enhancement', 'color': '009800'}]",[],7,"As a follow up to #128 

> I don't remember why I chose to do it that way (I wrote the compiler code two years ago) but indeed atm you can only choose a directory. I think there is no need to do it that way anymore so I might change that for v4.7 (maybe open a new issue that request for the full compiler path). 

As you may guess I explicit ask for changing this in 4.6.2 as 4.7 is a long way to go - and I'd expect most users to switch to the new IDE as it's target to be release on the same time.",{},{}
13281,IssuesEvent,2015-09-22 06:37:53+00:00,12024604,OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE,6699539,GitMensch,6609701,OpenCobolIDE,opened,[Enhancement] Offset calculator pane: enable sizable columns,[],[],0,"The current version has all columns with the same size. This wastes much place on the Level (which has only a maximum size of 2) and Offset (which is not very likely [but possible] to have a size more than 6) and often shortens the variable name.

As opinions which column should have what size likely differ (and actually may depend on the current source) I suggest to simply make the columns sizable",{},{}
13283,IssuesEvent,2016-02-25 09:27:06+00:00,12024604,OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE,1681217,ColinDuquesnoy,6609701,OpenCobolIDE,closed,"Split ""files with COBOL syntax highlighting"" and ""associated file extensions for compiler""","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff'}]",[],1,"### Description

OCIDE currently provides COBOL syntax highlighting (including navigation tree) for all files that match the ""associated file extensions for compiler"".

As no one wants to compile a copybook (or other local preparser formats) it would be nice to add a file extension list to the preferences tab ""code highlighting"".
All files that match one of these would be highlighted and the navigation tree would be used, but only the ones that are in the compiler tab enable background compilation and compile/run buttons.

",{},{}
13284,IssuesEvent,2016-11-05 14:23:41+00:00,12024604,OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE,1681217,ColinDuquesnoy,6609701,OpenCobolIDE,closed,FR for showing the available compiler flags,"[{'id': 51529256, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/OpenCobolIDE/OpenCobolIDE/labels/Enhancement', 'name': 'Enhancement', 'color': '009800', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'ColinDuquesnoy', 'id': 1681217, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1681217?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/ColinDuquesnoy', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ColinDuquesnoy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",1,"Can we include an option to show the available compiler flags? I think of a button right to the ""extra compiler flags"" that internally calls the configured compiler with the option `--help` and shows the result to the user with to option to use copy&paste to get them in the compiler flags.

The perfect solution (not part of this feature request) would be to parse the output, show a list of the available options in a popup (suppressing -help -i -V and the compiler flags we have in the IDE already) and let the user select via checkbox for each to include them in the ""extra compiler flags"". Not part of te FR as this is likely quite more work than only presenting the list.
",{},{}
