13377,IssuesEvent,2018-08-08 22:03:53+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,10146011,JasonRShaver,6844498,Azure,closed,Improve method of asserting that specific errors occur during tests.,"[{'id': 418947189, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MTg5NDcxODk=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Feature', 'name': 'Feature', 'color': '006b75', 'default': False}, {'id': 418934896, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MTg5MzQ4OTY=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/P2', 'name': 'P2', 'color': 'd93f0b', 'default': False}, {'id': 420278506, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MjAyNzg1MDY=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Test', 'name': 'Test', 'color': '006b75', 'default': False}]",[],3,"With VCRTestBase we had the ability to allow commands to succeed if an expected error was encountered.

The current scenario test allows for ""expect_failure"" but it will allow the command to succeed if ANY error is encountered.

The mechanism of using:
```Python
with self.assertRaises(CLIError):
   self.cmd(...)
```

Doesn't work consistently and is requiring changing CLIError to AssertRaises. This may be an unintended side effect of the Knack conversion.

Currently we are working around this, but we should develop a comprehensive solution and update these cases.",{},{}
