14799,IssuesEvent,2015-11-14 11:16:31+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,106176,kuba,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,"letsencrypt-apache is versioned ""0"" in PyPI json output","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/pkging', 'name': 'pkging', 'color': '000000'}]",[],1,"The version of letsencrypt-apache is ""0"" from PyPI json output currently whilst other letsencrypt packages isn't. There is also an empty ""0"" release inside the releases array of letsencrypt-apache only. This confused my version check script :/

Any chance that this could be fixed?

FYI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/letsencrypt-apache/json",{},{}
14806,IssuesEvent,2015-11-05 02:30:50+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,opened,Vendorize ConfigArgParse rather than pulling it from a private user repo.,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/letsencrypt-auto', 'name': 'letsencrypt-auto', 'color': '00a080'}]",[],0,"(1) This means everyone's fetching code from Kuba's repo, which is ok for experimental beta hacking but not for release
(2) The version pin produces an annoying message in the middle of -auto runs:

`Requirement already satisfied (use --upgrade to upgrade): ConfigArgParse from git+https://github.com/kuba/ConfigArgParse.git@python2.6-0.9.3#egg=ConfigArgParse in /tmp/throwaway/lib/python2.7/site-packages (from -r py26reqs.txt (line 1))`.",{},{}
14809,IssuesEvent,2015-09-11 17:51:37+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,1581662,jdkasten,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Feature request: automatically add the secured domain to HTTPS Everywhere,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff'}]",[],4,"Let's Encrypt has an option to set all the pages on a Web server to redirect to HTTPS from HTTP. When this option is used, it makes sense to automatically add corresponding rules to HTTPS Everywhere in order to help securing the site from an attempt to drop HTTPS at the first redirect.

Integration of that sort between two important and valuable EFF concepts tends to help in promoting both products and securing the Internet communications, doesn't it? :-)",{},{}
14813,IssuesEvent,2016-02-03 01:40:27+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,649860,SwartzCr,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,letsencrypt renew should imply non-interactive,[],[],1,"I think this behavior is somewhat confusing, but multiple other contributors want this change and we're moving forward with it. It simplifies running `letsencrypt renew` in cron.",{},{}
14819,IssuesEvent,2015-10-22 00:07:36+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Sphinx docs no longer build off of PyPi,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'bfd4f2'}]",[],3,"Well, this is a bit tricky.  Because the sphinx documentation build process reads the actual code to help generate the docs, we are seeing problems when using the tarballs that come out of PyPi.  The documentation makes references to code that's no longer shipped - letsencrypt_apache, letsencrypt_nginx, letsencrypt_compatibility_test, and letshelp_letsencrypt_*.

I'm not entirely sure how to solve this.  If we move the documentation that refers to the other modules into those tarballs and try to build it there, will it build correctly based on the code installed in the system paths?

@kuba, @fmarier, I'd love both of your input here.

