14937,IssuesEvent,2018-04-24 16:27:39+00:00,26876372,dateutil/dateutil,1377457,pganssle,9849410,dateutil,closed,[Feature Request] Adding the ability to disable automatic century detection,"[{'id': 149492527, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 177049992, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/parser', 'name': 'parser', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}, {'id': 149492531, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff', 'default': True}]",[],2,"Currently `dateutil` would try converting two-digit years, and [here](http://labix.org/python-dateutil/#head-19e5d3331806e55ec2ba1b9e39458784cc0a0004) is the corresponding section in the doc describing its behavior.

While it's generally helpful, there're still specific cases where it's a pain. E.g. a user may want all two-digit year values to be regarded as in the 1900s.

Currently it's possible to disable automatic century detection by sub-classing the `dateutil.parser.parserinfo` class, or via a patch like this:
```
>>> import dateutil.parser
>>> dateutil.parser.parse('65-12-01')
datetime.datetime(2065, 12, 1, 0, 0)
>>> old_init = dateutil.parser._parser._ymd.__init__
>>> def new_init(self, *args, **kwargs):
...   old_init(self, *args, **kwargs)
...   self.century_specified = True
... 
>>> dateutil.parser._parser._ymd.__init__ = new_init
>>> dateutil.parser.parse('65-12-01')
datetime.datetime(65, 12, 1, 0, 0)
```

I suppose it might be a good idea to include the feature as an optional argument of `dateutil.parser.parse`.",{},{}
