16703,IssuesEvent,2015-12-30 21:08:35+00:00,1843992,jazzband/django-pipeline,44535,cyberdelia,15129049,jazzband,closed,How to do a S3 + Cached + GZipped storage class?,[],[],8,"Here is my current attempt, with DEBUG=False:

```python
from django.contrib.staticfiles.storage import CachedFilesMixin, \
    StaticFilesStorage
from django.conf import settings

from pipeline.storage import PipelineMixin, GZIPMixin

from storages.backends.s3boto import S3BotoStorage
class S3PipelineStorage(PipelineMixin, CachedFilesMixin, GZIPMixin, S3BotoStorage):
    bucket_name = settings.PIPELINE_S3_BUCKET
    auto_create_bucket = True
    preload_metadata = True
    querystring_auth = False
    url_protocol = 'https:'
    gzip = True
```

However, when I collectstatic, I don't see any gzipping happening. When I check the rendering on the app server, no .gz suffixes are appearing, either.

I suspect this is a question of getting the right order and mixins. Am I missing something?

Not sure if this is relevant, but I also have the following STATICFILES_FINDERS specified on the production server:

```python
STATICFILES_FINDERS = (
    'django.contrib.staticfiles.finders.FileSystemFinder',
    'django.contrib.staticfiles.finders.AppDirectoriesFinder',
    'pipeline.finders.PipelineFinder',
)
```

Wasn't sure if that last one was needed with the S3 backend.",{},{}
16709,IssuesEvent,2017-08-12 20:34:02+00:00,924812,jazzband/django-constance,4428426,gb119,15129049,jazzband,opened,Bad effects on python2 to python3 migration....,[],[],0,"### Describe the problem

This is probably a bit of a corner case, but I recently migrated a Django codebase from Python 2.7 to 3.6 and hit a problem with DateTime values stored in a constance database backed. The issue is that the pickled data was not unpickling properly and the underlying django-picklefield was returning the raw string object if the unpickle failed.

It seems that it is simply really hard to get a DateTime pickled in 2.7 to unpickle nicely in 3.6, but this is the sort of thing I can live with. The unfortunate bit is that constance doesn't seem to have a guard for picklefield returning the raw string and that crashes the Admin pages (it also crashed my app, but that's my problem!) - it probably shouldn't do that.... A better behaviour would be to put up a warning on the Admin pages to the effect that there is possible data corruption.

There is a work-around by using the constance command line interface to set the constants back to a valid datetime (it would be even nicer to have a 'reset' in the command interface to simple reset them to the default values) and the admin pages could be loaded again.

### Steps to reproduce

Setup constance to store some DateTime data whilst running a Python 2.7 codebase.
Upgrade to Python 3.x
Try to use the constance admin pages to look at the constance variables

### System configuration

* Django version: 1.11.1
* Python version: from 2.7.11 switching to 3.6.2
",{},{}
16711,IssuesEvent,2016-10-10 20:57:52+00:00,924812,jazzband/django-constance,2865885,felixxm,15129049,jazzband,opened,Can't compare offset-naive and offset-aware datetimes,[],[],0,"### Describe the problem

`TypeError at /admin/constance/config/:`
`can't compare offset-naive and offset-aware datetimes`

### Steps to reproduce

Use datetime object at `CONSTANCE_CONFIG` with default value without localize:
```!python
USE_TZ = True
TIME_ZONE = 'Europe/Warsaw'
CONSTANCE_CONFIG = {
    'DISABLE_ORDERS_UNTIL':
        (
            datetime(2016, 1, 2, 12),
            'redacted',
            datetime,
        ),
```
Click `save` in `admin/constance/config/`.

### System configuration

* Django version: 1.10.2
* Python version: 2.7, 3.4, 3.5
",{},{}
