17276,IssuesEvent,2018-02-28 07:00:42+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,13256583,czastack,17565521,pybind,opened,Problem about upgrading to v2.2,[],[],0,"I have two problem about upgrading to v2.2.
First, it's not supported to do that as below at this version? I got ""error C2440"". I know that I can use lambda or function instead.
```c++
class Example
{
};

class PyExample
{
public:
    using Example::Example;

    void fn() { }
};
```

```c++
py::class_<Example, PyExample>(m, ""Example"")
    .def(py::init<>())
    .def(""fn"", &PyExample::fn)
```

Second, I want to call a initialize function of a c++ type after the construction of instance is completed. Because I need to call py::cast(this) in it. The function may do something like inc_ref.
In the older version, I add extention like that:
```c++
namespace pybind11 {
    template <typename... options>
    class class_t : public class_<options...>
    {
    public:
        using class_::class_;

        template <typename... Args, typename... Extra>
        auto &def_init(const detail::init<Args...> &init, const Extra&... extra)
        {
            def(""__init__"", [](type *self_, Args... args) { (new (self_) type(args...)->*(&type::__init))(); }, extra...);
            return *this;
        }
    }
}
```
In the old version it work well. And after I use v2.2.2, I modify it into:
```c++
namespace pybind11 {
    template <typename type_, typename... options>
    class class_t : public class_<type_, options...>
    {
    public:
        using class_::class_;

        template <typename... Args, typename... Extra>
        class_ &def_init(const detail::initimpl::constructor<Args...> &init, const Extra&... extra)
        {
            using namespace detail::initimpl;
            def(""__init__"", [](detail::value_and_holder &v_h, Args... args) {
                type_ *ins = construct_or_initialize<type_, Args...>(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
                v_h.value_ptr() = ins;
                (ins->*(&type_::__init))();
            }, detail::is_new_style_constructor(), extra...);

            return *this;
        }
    };
}
```
But, if the __init function do something will make the reference count increasing, the c++ instance will call destructor early.
For example:

```c++
void View::__init()
{
    py::cast(this).inc_ref();
}
```
",{},{}
17282,IssuesEvent,2018-06-01 01:59:09+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,2520133,bjfar,17565521,pybind,opened,Problems with transitive link dependencies,[],[],0,"I am having some link problems with pybind11. I am wrapping a small piece of code, which links to a C API shared library that I build with cmake in a separate project. This external library has its own dependencies, which in principle should be found in the INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES property that is filled by FindPackage.

To be explicit, my CMakeLists.txt file looks like this:

```
find_package(ScannerBitCAPI REQUIRED)
get_target_property(LIBS ScannerBitCAPI INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES)
message(""Libs: ${LIBS}"")

# We will use pybind11 to create the Python extension module
add_subdirectory(""${PROJECT_SOURCE_DIR}/lib/pybind11-2.1.1"")

# Generate Python module
pybind11_add_module(pyscannerbit ""${PROJECT_SOURCE_DIR}/src/pyScannerBit.cpp"")
target_link_libraries(pyscannerbit PUBLIC ScannerBitCAPI)
```

Everything builds fine, but when I try to import the python module I get unresolved symbols that indicate that the transitive link dependencies are not propagating properly. For example I get

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""example.py"", line 1, in <module>
    from sb import Scan, HDF5
  File ""/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/contrib/pyscannerbit/sb.py"", line 12, in <module>
    import pyscannerbit
ImportError: /home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libUtils.so: undefined symbol: recursive_mkdir
```

where this symbol can be found in the library libmkpath.so:

```
> nm /home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libmkpath.so
 ...CUT...
0000000000000830 T recursive_mkdir
...CUT...
```

which seems to be correctly listed under the LIBS that I extract (just for debugging purposes) from INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES:

```
Libs: /home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/contrib/yaml-cpp-0.5.3/libyaml-cpp.a;/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libPrinters.so;/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libmkpath.so;/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libfjcore.so;/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libLogs.so;/home/farmer/repos/gambit/copy4/lib/libUtils.so;/usr/lib/openmpi/lib/libmpi_cxx.so;/usr/lib/openmpi/lib/libmpi.so;/usr/lib/openmpi/lib/libmpi.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libdl.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libgsl.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libgslcblas.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libm.so;/home/farmer/anaconda3/envs/gambit/lib/libhdf5.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/librt.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libpthread.so;/home/farmer/anaconda3/envs/gambit/lib/libz.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libdl.so;/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libm.so
```

Do you have any idea what my problem might be? INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES seems to be filled correctly, so I want to blame pybind11 for not linking them into the final python extension module, but it is of course possible that I have done something stupid or wrong here :). If it helps, I am building and exporting the cmake config info for the other project using the method described here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33462209/making-cmake-library-accessible-by-other-cmake-packages-automatically/33568871#33568871.",{},{}
17292,IssuesEvent,2016-04-14 09:27:40+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1203629,wjakob,17565521,pybind,closed,CMake finding Python library and Python interpreter mismatch during pybind11 build,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pybind/pybind11/labels/build%20system%20issue', 'name': 'build system issue', 'color': '207de5'}]",[],7,"CMake finds  mismatched PythonLibs and PythonInterp on my machine with multiple Python installations. PythonLibs finds 2.7.10, while PythonInterp finds 2.7.11:

    $ cmake .
    -- Setting build type to 'MinSizeRel' as none was specified.
    -- Found PythonLibs: /usr/lib/libpython2.7.dylib (found version ""2.7.10"")
    CMake Error at /usr/local/Cellar/cmake/3.4.1/share/cmake/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:148 (message):
      Could NOT find PythonInterp: Found unsuitable version ""2.7.11"", but
      required is exact version ""2.7.10"" (found /usr/local/bin/python2.7)
    Call Stack (most recent call first):
      /usr/local/Cellar/cmake/3.4.1/share/cmake/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:386 (_FPHSA_FAILURE_MESSAGE)
      /usr/local/Cellar/cmake/3.4.1/share/cmake/Modules/FindPythonInterp.cmake:162 (FIND_PACKAGE_HANDLE_STANDARD_ARGS)
      CMakeLists.txt:37 (find_package)

    -- Configuring incomplete, errors occurred!
    See also ""/Users/jthetzel/src/pybind11/CMakeFiles/CMakeOutput.log"".


Specifying -DPYTHON_INCLUDE_DIR seems to bypass the error, though it warns that EXACT is being ignored. However, PythonInterp now finds Python 3.5.1:

    $ rm CMakeCache.txt
    $ cmake -DPYTHON_INCLUDE_DIR=/usr/local/bin/python .
    -- Setting build type to 'MinSizeRel' as none was specified.
    -- Found PythonLibs: /usr/lib/libpython2.7.dylib
    CMake Warning (dev) at CMakeLists.txt:37 (find_package):
      Ignoring EXACT since no version is requested.
    This warning is for project developers.  Use -Wno-dev to suppress it.

    -- Found PythonInterp: /usr/local/bin/python3.5 (found version ""3.5.1"")
    -- Performing Test HAS_CPP14_FLAG
    -- Performing Test HAS_CPP14_FLAG - Success
    -- Performing Test HAS_CPP11_FLAG
    -- Performing Test HAS_CPP11_FLAG - Success
    -- Performing Test HAS_LTO_FLAG
    -- Performing Test HAS_LTO_FLAG - Success
    -- Configuring done
    -- Generating done
    -- Build files have been written to: /Users/jthetzel/src/pybind11


I have three Pythons installed, 2.7.11 and 3.5.1 via homebrew in `/usr/local/bin/`, and 2.7.10 via the OSX system installation in `/usr/bin/`:

    $ which -a python
    /usr/local/bin/python
    /usr/bin/python

    $ which -a python3
    /usr/local/bin/python3

    $ /usr/local/bin/python --version
    Python 2.7.11
    $ /usr/bin/python --version
    Python 2.7.10
    $ /usr/local/bin/python3 --version
    Python 3.5.1


`/usr/local/bin/python` is expected to be found first in PATH:

    $ echo $PATH
    /Users/jthetzel/.local/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin:/opt/X11/bin

    $ python --version
    Python 2.7.11


From a related closed pull request, this appears to be the fault of CMake ( https://github.com/wjakob/pybind11/pull/65 ), not specifically pybind11. Still, it would be nice to have a safe workaround, as having homebrew and system Python installations will likely be common for users in OSX environments. I'll take a closer look tonight.

Some version information:

    $ sw_vers
    ProductName:	Mac OS X
    ProductVersion:	10.11.3
    BuildVersion:	15D21

    $ cmake --version
    cmake version 3.4.1

    $ git rev-parse --short HEAD
    4f8902a
",{},{}
17306,IssuesEvent,2018-06-06 14:15:15+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,32247590,phil-zxx,17565521,pybind,opened,Odd Conversion Error from 'unsigned __int64' to 'unsigned __int64 *',[],[],0,"Let me outline all the steps I've taken:
1. Downloaded https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/archive/v2.2.3.zip and 
extracted it to C:\pybind11-2.2.3\

2. As per http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basics.html#windows I create a folder **build**, i.e. **C:\pybind11-2.2.3\build\** and then run **cmake -A x64 ..** in there (since my Python is 64 bit).
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32247590/41042824-83053f5e-699a-11e8-949e-9b07ce381e4b.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32247590/41042877-a234df1a-699a-11e8-93e4-3d35bcb07eb2.png)

3. Now I run **cmake --build . --config Release --target check** but get a lot of conversion errors:
`vector(2326): error C2446: '<': no conversion from 'unsigned __int64' to 'unsigned __int64 *'`
Here a screenshot
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32247590/41043028-ec001dda-699a-11e8-8645-74af1585e31a.png)
Similarly, when building from the VS solution **pybind11.sln** directly:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32247590/41043335-a5340668-699b-11e8-8598-0dc157c0cb2c.png)

---

I am using **cmake** as per https://cmake.org/files/v3.11/cmake-3.11.3-win64-x64.zip
and **Visual Studio 2017 Professional**. I've searched stackexchange & google for this sort of error but cannot find anything. Has anybody an idea what the root cause of this is? Am I missing any packages/libraries or else (like specific build parameters)?",{},{}
17312,IssuesEvent,2016-11-28 23:21:14+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,654621,halgari,17565521,pybind,closed,py::args doesn't work with C++ methods?,[],[],4,"I have a class that looks something like this:

```
class Foo {
public:
  void __call__(py::args args);
}
```

From what I can tell the problem is that pybind11 doesn't support positional args in conjunction with `py::args`. However since this is a method it will always have a `self` positional argument before the `py::args`, is it really impossible to use `py::arg` in conjunction with a class method?",{},{}
17315,IssuesEvent,2018-01-06 15:51:39+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1381301,ppwwyyxx,17565521,pybind,opened,Let C++ function return bytes without extra copy,[],[],0,"Make sure you've completed the following steps before submitting your issue -- thank you!

## Issue description
According to the documentation, to let a C++ function which returns `std::string` produces bytes instead of unicode string in Python, one needs to use `py::byte`: http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/cast/strings.html?highlight=string#return-c-strings-without-conversion.

However I found that `py::byte` wraps around `PyBytes_FromString` function, which copies the string according to https://docs.python.org/3/c-api/bytes.html#c.PyBytes_FromString.

Is there anyway to construct a `bytes` object directly in C++ without an extra copy?",{},{}
