17710,IssuesEvent,2017-07-21 17:47:08+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SOS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,closed,derived hosts.,"[{'id': 325435541, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/discussion', 'name': 'discussion', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': False}, {'id': 546253590, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/remote%20host', 'name': 'remote host', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 325435539, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/request', 'name': 'request', 'color': '159818', 'default': False}]",[],1,"We have had examples of 

```
hosts:
     h1:
        queue: short
        job_template: ... ${queue}
      h2:
        queue: long
        job_template: ... ${queue}
```

so it makes sense to copy definition of a host to another while allowing modification. In this way, the above could be written as

```
hosts:
     h1:
        queue: short
        job_template: ... ${queue}
      h2:
        based_on: h1
        queue: long
```

An additional use of this mechanism is to create alias for a long name. For example, if there are many hosts in `hosts.yml` that are difficult to remember, users could do

```
sos config --global --set hosts.A.based_on a_very_long_name
```
and then `A` could be used as an alias to `a_very_long_name`.

Implementation wise, it can be trouble to handle nested `based_on`, even chained `based_on`.",{},{}
17718,IssuesEvent,2017-05-18 16:12:09+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SOS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,closed,Number of tasks per submitted job,"[{'id': 546253590, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/remote%20host', 'name': 'remote host', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 325435539, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/request', 'name': 'request', 'color': '159818', 'default': False}]",[],31,"Suppose I have this situation:

```
[1]
parameter: seed = [x for x in range(1000)]
input: for_each = ['seed']
task:
R:
  set.seed(${_seed})
  ...
```

This will generate 1000 tasks, therefore 1000 HPC jobs. This sounds like a burden in many ways. I wonder if we can have some task option:

```
task: task_per_job = 20
```
and, 

```
task: total_jobs = 50
```

In the first case, SoS will put 20 tasks in one HPC job and submit 50 jobs. In the 2nd case, we tell SoS that we want to submit 50 jobs total and SoS will figure out how many tasks per job, in this case is 20. 

I under stand we do have the `max_job` option. But that still will result in submitting 1000 jobs in the end, though sequentially reather than at once. I think these two options would be great features to have.",{},{}
17726,IssuesEvent,2018-01-21 19:10:46+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SoS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,closed,Improved error info for step processes,[],[],5,"This is a complementary issue to #834 : I recently got user feedback complaining that debugging in step process is difficult, when writing python scripts directly into SoS steps. For example:

```
[global]
def bad_print():
    print(f'{[1,2,3](9)}')

[1]
print(""hi from SoS"")
bad_print()
```

The error message is:

```
ERROR: [default_1]: TypeError at line 2 of 
    print(""hi from SoS"")
>>> bad_print()
'list' object is not callable
```

The problem is that the user has no idea which line of `bad_print()` complains. `-v4` gives:

```
    exec(script, _dict)
  File ""<string>"", line 2, in <module>
  File ""<string>"", line 2, in bad_print
TypeError: 'list' object is not callable
```

In this MWE it is trivial to realize that indeed the 2nd line of `[global]` is problematic. But when `global` gets complicated and without any line numbers in SoS Notebook it is difficult to determine where the problem is. The `<string>` can be different from the physical text in SoS script. This MWE might not be very convincing but I hope I've conveyed the idea. I'll try come up with better examples if something more convincing is needed. The error that the user actually has run into was impossible to pin-point that he ended up copying the entire thing to a pure python notebook to debug. 

",{},{}
17736,IssuesEvent,2018-02-05 14:36:33+00:00,120299031,gisaia/ARLAS-server,9483289,elouanKeryell-Even,20204404,gisaia,closed,Refactor sort API,[],"[{'login': 'MohamedHamouGisaia', 'id': 26741864, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/26741864?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/MohamedHamouGisaia', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/MohamedHamouGisaia/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",1,"In gitlab by @sylvaingaudan on Apr 19, 2017, 17:13

