18212,IssuesEvent,2017-03-06 14:39:48+00:00,68376693,pybel/pybel,5069736,cthoyt,22892058,pybel,closed,Graph Data Management,"[{'id': 443704419, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pybel/pybel/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 540964709, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pybel/pybel/labels/hard', 'name': 'hard', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}, {'id': 540965220, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pybel/pybel/labels/high%20priority', 'name': 'high priority', 'color': 'd93f0b', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'cthoyt', 'id': 5069736, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/5069736?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/cthoyt', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/cthoyt/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",1,"This is the monolithic to-do for the data manager portion of the project. This consists of translating the `Django` models used in the AETIONOMY Knowledgebase to use `SQLlchemy`. 

For the first try, do **NOT** focus on speed. We need a working implementation first before optimizing. This should all be done in beautiful, idiomatic python, and take full advantage of the `SQLAlchemy` ORM. This also means that `pandas` is unacceptable.

## Production ready

- [x] Add model for network metadata. Include the pickled graph. (`pybel.manager.models.Network`)
- [x] Input and output of network object in Graph Cache Manager (`pybel.manager.graph_cache.GraphCacheManager`)

## Still needs reinvestigation

- [x] Add models to `pybel.manager`
- [x] Implement `pybel.to_database(belgraph, conn_str)`
- [x] Implement `pybel.from_database(conn_str)`

Reinvestigate all code:
- [ ] Add docs to all models
- [x] Add ORM information, like `relationship()` to automatically make joins
- [x] Use proper session querying, like `session.query(models.Namespace).filter(models.Namespace.keyword == 'HGNC').one()` and transaction management at the `session` level",{},{}
18221,IssuesEvent,2017-11-06 10:53:25+00:00,7308334,ParallelSSH/parallel-ssh,6331523,moneill-mw,22918200,ParallelSSH,opened,Add scp (non-SFTP) support,[],[],0,"__Current behaviour:__
I am targetting an embedded device (and have limited ability to install software) which is running dropbear (2017.75).  
When I try to use the existing `copy_file` method I get this exception
```Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.4/site-packages/paramiko/sftp_client.py"", line 103, in __init__
    server_version = self._send_version()
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.4/site-packages/paramiko/sftp.py"", line 107, in _send_version
    t, data = self._read_packet()
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.4/site-packages/paramiko/sftp.py"", line 174, in _read_packet
    x = self._read_all(4)
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.4/site-packages/paramiko/sftp.py"", line 161, in _read_all
    raise EOFError()
```
When I look at the dropbear logs on the device, I see
```
[1204] Nov 06 11:19:43 User usr1 executing '/usr/libexec/sftp-server'
```
but there is no /usr/libexec/sftp-server on the device and I cannot install one.  

I am able to work around this issue by monkey-patching [scp.py](https://github.com/jbardin/scp.py) into the paramiko client.  
```
def fake_copy_scp(self, local_file, remote_file, recurse=False, sftp=None):
    print(""fake_copy(%s,%s)""%(local_file, remote_file))
    scpclient = scp.SCPClient(self.client.get_transport())
    scpclient.put(local_file, remote_file)
    scpclient.close()

# Monkey-patch
#pssh.pssh_client.SSHClient.copy_file = fake_copy_scp
```
which then let my copy succeed
```
greenlets = client.copy_file('file.txt', 'file.txt')
joinall(greenlets, raise_error=True)
```
__Desired behaviour:__ 
The existing sftp copy_file functionality is more functional (recursive copy, create remote folder, etc) than the scp.py copy and is definitely to be preferred when the remote servers can support it, but it would be useful to have the (limited/less performant) scp copy behaviour available for use when the remote servers cannot support it without resorting to monkey-patching.  

For my use-case, the addition of a `copy_file_scp(localfile, remotefile)` method would be sufficient.  Support for globbing and/or recursive-copy etc would be nice-to-haves.

Alternatively, some sort of interface which would allow ""plugging-in"" scp.py operation should also work
```
client = ParallelSSHClient(hosts)
operation = SCPCopier(""localfile"", ""remotefile"")
greenlets = client.execute_operation(operation)
```
__Additional info:__ python=3.4.5, OS=CentOS7.4, parallel-ssh=1.2.0, paramiko=2.1.4, ssh2-python=0.6.0
The scp.py module works with the paramiko client, but would need rework/adapting to work with the ssh2 client
",{},{}
