18389,IssuesEvent,2018-07-29 14:47:57+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,1160460,sorcio,26335827,python-trio,opened,test_SocketType_resolve fails,[],[],0,"Apparently on Mac, on *some* setups, `getaddrinfo()` will always return IPv4 mapped addresses regardless of whether the AI_V4MAPPED is actually set. This causes failures in this assertion https://github.com/python-trio/trio/blob/fd0d8770a120a09a506ccd8a3f9969b26a22f38e/trio/tests/test_socket.py#L420-L422

This is probably a system configuration issue and maybe there is not much we can do about it. But it's causing our tests to fail on some machines. I've seen this happen regularly on my work laptop for some time (macOS 10.13.5, Python 3.6 and 3.7) and a couple other sprinters at EuroPython had the same issue. Good news is that it doesn't affect our Mac CI.

One potential (maybe not ideal) solution is to verify whether the system has this quirk and in that case skip the test.

### Details

Calling getaddrinfo() on an IPv4 address, with AF_INET6 and the AI_V4MAPPED flag returns an IPv4-mapped IPv6 address. This is documented and works in all platforms.

```python
>>> getaddrinfo('1.2.3.4', 0, AF_INET6, SOCK_STREAM, 0, AI_V4MAPPED)
[(<AddressFamily.AF_INET6: 30>, <SocketKind.SOCK_STREAM: 1>, 6, '', ('::ffff:1.2.3.4', 0, 0, 0))]
```

If I only want IPv6 addresses I won't set the AI_V4MAPPED and I won't get any result back. For example, this is what happens on Linux:

```
>>> s.getaddrinfo('1.2.3.4', 0, s.AF_INET6, s.SOCK_STREAM, 0, 0)
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.7/socket.py"", line 748, in getaddrinfo
    for res in _socket.getaddrinfo(host, port, family, type, proto, flags):
socket.gaierror: [Errno -9] Address family for hostname not supported
```

But if I try the same on my Mac I still get the IPv4-mapped results, even though I shouldn't!

```python
>>> getaddrinfo('1.2.3.4', 0, AF_INET6, SOCK_STREAM, 0, 0)
[(<AddressFamily.AF_INET6: 30>, <SocketKind.SOCK_STREAM: 1>, 6, '', ('::ffff:1.2.3.4', 0, 0, 0))]
```
",{},{}
18432,IssuesEvent,2017-10-26 20:22:29+00:00,96581030,census-instrumentation/opencensus-python,12888824,liyanhui1228,26944525,census-instrumentation,closed,Change FixedRateSampler sampling rule,[],[],0,,{},{}
18433,IssuesEvent,2018-08-25 01:31:48+00:00,96581030,census-instrumentation/opencensus-python,4898263,odeke-em,26944525,census-instrumentation,closed,ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'google.cloud*',[],[],2,"Making this issue so future Python developers scratching their heads will have a solution:

After debugging for hours to get a simple [trace](https://github.com/orijtech/opencensus-for-grpc-python-developers) to run, here was the fix:

1. Remove all pip modules (you could probably get away with only removing all google cloud related modules)
2. Install `grcpio-tools`, `opencensus`, and `google-cloud-trace`

```
[WARNING: REMOVES ALL PIP MODULES] sudo pip3 freeze | sudo xargs pip3 uninstall -y
python3 -m pip install grpcio-tools opencensus google-cloud-trace
```

There are two issues out in the wild that are causing this:

* Installations of google cloud python libraries (such as `gcloud` or `google-cloud`) cause other `No Module named 'google.cloud.*'` errors
* I can't find any online documentation mentioning that google-cloud-trace is needed.

Having mention of `google-cloud-trace` on the README.md would be helpful.

Cheers!",{},{}
18441,IssuesEvent,2018-04-19 12:54:58+00:00,1207377,python-needle/needle,530560,jorenko,27863081,python-needle,opened,Element screenshots incorrect when page has been scrolled,[],[],0,"When the page has been scrolled, the element coordinates returned by NeedleWebElementMixin.get_dimensions() are relative to the top-left of the page, but the screenshot that get_screenshot() crops starts at the current scroll position. This results in the returned screenshot being of either the wrong part of the page or mostly/all blank, depending on the browser. To fix this, the current scroll position needs to be subtracted from the position, like so:


diff --git a/home/jjurack/.local/share/virtualenvs/test_web-6ViYfjms/lib/python3.6/site-packages/needle/driver-orig.py b/home/jjurack/.local/share/virtualenvs/test_web-6ViYfjms/lib/python3.6/site-packages/needle/driver.py
index cd10b49..eceafe5 100644
--- a/home/jjurack/.local/share/virtualenvs/test_web-6ViYfjms/lib/python3.6/site-packages/needle/driver-orig.py
+++ b/home/jjurack/.local/share/virtualenvs/test_web-6ViYfjms/lib/python3.6/site-packages/needle/driver.py
@@ -63,8 +63,8 @@ class NeedleWebElementMixin(object):
         d = self.get_dimensions()
         
         # Cast values to int in order for _ImageCrop not to break
-        d['left'] = int(d['left'])
-        d['top'] = int(d['top'])
+        d['left'] = int(d['left']) - self._parent.execute_script('return window.scrollX')
+        d['top'] = int(d['top']) - self._parent.execute_script('return window.scrollY')
         d['width'] = int(d['width'])
         d['height'] = int(d['height'])
",{},{}
18445,IssuesEvent,2018-08-22 15:35:13+00:00,1380748,ninia/jep,13338101,bsteffensmeier,28115331,ninia,closed,Is jep correct solution for my problem?,[],[],1,"I want to call some python scripts from java by sending some data to them and also receive back some return values from python scripts. Currently I am sending the scripts and the input data as json string along with some metadata to python and obtaining the output of python scripts along with some metadata in java by communicating over tcp sockets. I am currently using pandas and numpy in my python script and handled the communication of pandas and numpy objects through json sent to / from java and python.

Earlier I evaluated various options I had in [this stackoverflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39410339/different-better-approaches-for-calling-python-function-from-java). I wasnt aware of jep at that time.

The requirements I explained in that thread are as follows:

- Call to python script from java should be transparent, in the sense that it should not require modifying `.py` file simply to enable it to be called from java. I might be given any python file with some functions inside it. I should be able to call any of these functions without requiring to modify `.py` file.
- I want to be able to send arguments of both primitive types (`int`, `String`, `floats` etc.) or non primitive types (`HashMap`,`ArrayList`) from java to python function and receive back the returned object (which may of primitive types or non-primitive types) from python to java. I am also using pandas DataFrame and numpy ndarray and hence also want to be able to send and receive corresponding objects to and from java and python.
- I *preferably* want to stick to CPython instead of Jython because I might need to use newer libraries that might not be available in Jython.

Ar these requirements are met jep?  I find following reasons for which jep is unsuitable for my requirements:
- jep does not allow python objects returned back to java (I might be grossly wrong here as I have not tried using Jep yet)
- creating sending and receiving pandas dataframe between java and python is not possible 

Am I right with this?
",{},{}
